			<ns0:name>ncb...@google.com</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/100032148147647801554/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">Platform: Linux, using recent Chrome binary and head-of-tree PPAPI plugin.

Problem: in srpc_basic_ppapi.html, the nexe method .char_array returns an object that almost behaves like an Array, but is actually an Object and this can cause problems.

For example, rev_val.join(&amp;quot;,&amp;quot;) works correctly, but ret_val.toString() does not because the method detects that ret_val is not actually an Array. (It throws a exception: Array.prototype.toString is not generic).  Arrays are special objects according to the language spec.  (See: http://perfectionkills.com/how-ecmascript-5-still-does-not-allow-to-subclass-an-array/ )

Instrumenting array_ppapi.cc shows that it creates Array objects correctly.  The problem is likely elsewhere.

Starting point: char_array is implemented in tests/srpc/srpc_test.c as the function CharArrayMethod  I would guess either the out_args are constructed wrong, or there's a object copy done incorrectly somewhere along the line.
